title: Two Southwest Boeing 737s clip wing tips in California
text:
Two Southwest Boeing 737s clip wing tips in California Last updated 07:51, September 1 2015 A photo posted by Manas G (@themanasutra) on Aug 30, 2015 at 9:31pm PDT 
Two commercial airliners clipped wing tips at the Oakland International Airport in California, but no injuries were reported. 
KNTV reports that a Southwest Airlines flight was headed to Orange County in Southern California when its wing came into contact with the wing of another plane, while pushing back from the gate. 
Passenger Manas Gowd said he was looking out the window when the plane lurched back from the gate and he felt a "very unnatural thump." He snapped a photo, showing a rugged edge of the upturned wing. "We quickly realised that a chunk of the plane wing had broken off and fallen to the tarmac. We flagged down a stewardess quickly and brought the matter to her attention as we had yet to stop moving backwards," Gowd told the Daily Mail. Passengers disembarked and the flight was cancelled. " We were first told that there was a plane waiting for us at an adjacent gate. Once we got there, we were told that there was no plane and that we were to go to the check-in counter for further information. After about two hours, I got a future travel voucher and a flight ticket for tomorrow," Gowd added. C'mon @SouthwestAir get it together. We're sitting stranded with no where to go. @RFWill149 
The other plane had arrived from Phoenix earlier on Sunday evening and was empty. 
Both planes were taken out of service and will undergo a maintenance check. 
"Safety is always our number one focus, and we are conducting an internal review to identify details surrounding yesterday's event," Eliasen said. "Our employees are working as quickly as possible to re-accommodate all customers," airline spokeswoman Alyssa Eliasen said.
